ne another, shaping a narrow field of livelihood options that women navigate daily. In the course of this rich ethnography, Shah discusses policing practices, migrants' access to housing and water, the idea of public space, critiques of states and citizenship, and the discursive location of violence within debates on sexual commerce. Throughout, the book analyzes the epistemology of prostitution, and the silences and secrets that constitute the discourse of sexual commerce on Mumbai's streets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107118200 cprintz978082235689940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376514?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822376514/original  a978-3-11-071182-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles